description.plain: “Love Affair” is apart of an ep Umi released in October 2019 called “Love Language” . The ep contains 4 songs. Love affair is about Umi having a relationship with a person and eventually starts catching feelings, but continues to tell herself its just a crush and nothing more.

body.plain: The song is about the process of finding your identity and letting go of the things that hold you back

annotations:
Nd I could be free again
 Free from my troubles and my sins
 Free from the tears inside
 And free from the fears I try to hide away, ’cause

“And I could be free again
Free from my troubles and my sins
Free from the tears inside
And free from the fears I try to hide away, ‘cause”

Sometimes running away from our problems seems like the lighter choice or path for us at the moment, but can you imagine feeling all of your fears and crying it all out to release the attachments? Things fall apart for us to find deeper meaning, to give us access to a lost part of ourselves that needed to surface through deep grief and discomfort. Being able to let go of all the negative emotions makes you feel free and that’s exactly what she was trying to show in her lyrics. Show your authentic self, don’t hide your beauty.

“Butterfly, butterfly
Take me on your wings and fly (oh)
Wish I was just like you
Maybe then I’ll see the light”

  Butterflies have always been a metaphor not only to people but in movies and books. They have the meaning of letting everything take time and to be able to let go. They are known that a small change can give rise to a big tidal wave, & you can’t predict where or how. Seemingly unimportant acts, or omissions, can have great and unforeseen consequences.

description.plain:
“Lullaby,”  is focused on the beginning of an important yet equally complicated relationship. The song is defined by its waltzy, lo-fi beat and wavy synth pads, inviting listeners into UMI’s constructed, dreamy landscape. Her voice complements the instrumental with grace. By the chorus, she sings, “Let me sing you a lullaby,” in an entrancing, whispery voice, proving that sometimes the most powerful vocal can be the quietest.

The second verse features Yeek presenting one of his most vocally dynamic performances thus far. His smooth voice lays suspended over the beat and presents a sort of call-and-response to UMI’s preceding verse. The SoCal based artist is known best for his blend of R&B and hip hop with west coaster surf rock and his collaboration with fellow Ones to Watch artist, Duckwrth.

As in most of UMI’s work, the song’s strength is reliant on its lyrics. In “Lullaby,” UMI begs for some way to help her partner – while she wants to be a calming presence, she feels he will not admit what has been bothering him. The song speaks to the helplessness of not knowing how to help someone and is a meditation on a relationship that lacks crucial communication.

Painfully, the song ends without resolve. Instead, UMI simply repeats, “When will you try to be okay?” This lack of resolution, however, is a major strength for the song, allowing space for listeners to apply their own experiences and to connect with its universal themes.

description.plain:
UMI is known to be a believer of spiritual practices such as manifesting.

She has a YouTube Show called “Full Moon With UMI” which dives more into her beliefs.

Here she seems to be “speaking into existence” the the things she wants for her life whether that be the state of her personal relationships, her material affluence or her self view.

One of the central themes of UMI’s beliefs is the idea that for one to be happy, one should learn to love themselves and exert the same kinds of behaviours they do on the ones they love to themselves.

One may think at first that in the hook UMI is apologising to a friend or family member but she is in fact talking to herself.

One of the most common things people who believe in manifesting and preach self love is the idea that the language we use towards ourselves is not often language we would use towards other people we love, as well as the idea that speech can literally bring things into our lives.

On the first lines of the Hook, UMI is apologising for disrespecting herself verbally in her head.

She then apologises for not valuing herself enough to trust her own instincts, but then reverts to how she speaks to herself and then promises to give herself more love.

This record is one of healing and vulnerability.  UMI comments on her personal relationship with her dad and wishes she was “cool” with her dad.

Whether this is because their relationship was hindered at the time this song was written is unknown, but letting her fans that close shows her bravery expressed through the vulnerability of this song.
